o, Sakyo-ku, Kyoto 606-8502, Japan; Ishii, M., Meteorological Research Institute, Japan Meteorological Agency, 1-1 Nagamine, Tsukuba, Ibaraki 305-0052, Japan; Kimoto, M., Center for Climate System Research, University of Tokyo, 5-1-5 Kashiwanoha, Kashiwa, Chiba 277-8568, Japan","A Predictable Component Analysis (PrCA) has been applied to near-term forecasts of ocean-atmosphere natural variability within a global warming scenario. The most predictable pattern in the North Pacific region on decadal time scales for the period 1965-1999 is a clockwise movement of heat content anomalies, which is composed of the eastward propagation along the Kuroshio-Oyashio extension (hereafter KOE) region and the subsequent southwestward propagation along the subduction pathway through the subtropical region. Our results also suggest the important role played by the westward traveling Rossby wave north of the KOE region in determining the phase change of the Pacific Decadal Oscillation (PDO) during this period. A comparative study with different initial conditions demonstrates the importance of proper thermal constraints on the ocean subsurface, in conjunction with the Rossby wave dynamics, for the initiation of predictable patterns in the heat content anomaly. Copyright 2009 by the American Geophysical Union.",,"Comparative studies; Component analysis; Decadal timescale; Eastward propagation; Heat contents; Initial conditions; Kuroshio; Natural variability; North Pacific; Ocean-atmosphere; Pacific decadal oscillation; Phase Change; Rossby wave; Subtropical regions; Thermal constraints; Enthalpy; Global warming; Weather forecasting; Ocean currents; climate prediction; comparative study; global warming; Pacific Decadal Oscillation; Rossby wave; subduction zone; subtropical region; wave propagation; Pacific Ocean; Pacific Ocean (North)",,,,,,"Bloom, S.C., Takacs, L.L., Da Silva, A.M., Ledvina, D., Data assimilation using incremental analysis updates (1996) Monthly Weather Review, 124 (6), pp. 1256-1271; Delsole, T.M., Chang, P., Predictable component analysis, canonical correlation analysis, and autoregressive models (2003) Journal of the Atmospheric Sciences, 60 (2), pp. 409-416; Gu, D., Philander, S.G.H., Interdecadal climate fluctuations that depend on exchanges between the tropics and extratropics (1997) Science, 275 (5301), pp. 805-807. , DOI 10.1126/science.275.5301.805; Hasumi, H., Emori, S., K-1 coupled model (MIROC) description (2004) K-1 Tech. Rep., 1, p. 34. , Cent. for Clim. Syst. Res., Univ. of Tokyo, Tokyo; Hoffman, R.N., Kalnay, E., Lagged average forecasting, an alternative to Monte Carlo forecasting (1983) Tellus, Ser. A, 35, pp. 100-118; Ishii, M., Kimoto, M., Kachi, M., Historical ocean subsurfaces temperature analysis with error estimates (2003) Monthly Weather Review, 131 (1), pp. 51-73; Killworth, P.D., Blundell, J., Large-scale propagating disturbances: Approximation by vertical normal modes (2001) J. Phys. Oceanogr., 31, pp. 2852-2870; Latif, M., Barnett, T.P., Causes of decadal climate variability over the North Pacific and North America (1994) Science, 266 (5185), pp. 634-637; Masuda, S., Role of the ocean in the decadal climate change in the North Pacific (2002) J. Geophys. Res., 107 (C12), p. 3224. , doi:10.1029/2002JC001420; Miller, A.J., Cayan, D.R., White, W.B., A westward intensified decadal change in the North Pacific thermocline and gyre-scale circulation (1998) J. Clim., 11, pp. 3112-3127; Nonaka, M., Xie, S.-P., Propagation of North Pacific interdecadal subsurface temperature anomalies in an ocean GCM (2000) Geophysical Research Letters, 27 (22), pp. 3747-3750. , DOI 10.1029/2000GL011488; Nonaka, M., Xie, S.-P., Covariations of sea surface temperature and wind over the Kuroshio and its extension: Evidence for ocean-to-atmosphere feedback (2003) Journal of Climate, 16 (9), pp. 1404-1413; Nozawa, T., Nagashima, T., Shiogama, H., Crooks, S.A., Detecting natural influence on surface air temperature change in the ear